Vibium Contribution Framework: Volunteer vs. Compensated Work

To maintain a healthy and fair ecosystem, Vibium clearly separates community-driven contributions from core operational work. This distinction protects our contributors, preserves open-source energy, and ensures that critical infrastructure work is reliably delivered and fairly compensated.

The Volunteer Sphere: Ambassadors & MVPs

The volunteer sphere is the engine of community growth, knowledge sharing, and ecosystem expansion.

Nature of Work:

Self-Directed: You choose what to work on based on your interests and creativity.

Flexible: There are no required hours, deadlines, or minimum coverage expectations.

Impact-Driven: Work is focused on experimentation, education, and brand building.

Rewards & Recognition:

Accumulation of Leaderboard points and Vibium Credits.

Early access to experimental features and private beta previews.

Opportunities for public recognition and speaking slots at community events.

1. Educational Content

Authoring tutorials for personal blogs or developer platforms.

Creating video demonstrations, explainers, or "build in public" experiments.

Sharing technical insights and architectural patterns on social channels.

2. Peer Support & Mentorship

Assisting other builders in the Discord community on an ad-hoc basis.

Participating in community calls and contributing to knowledge-sharing sessions.

Note: No volunteer is expected to provide continuous support or technical coverage.

3. Open Ecosystem Growth

Developing community-driven plugins or third-party integrations.

Organizing local meetups or representing Vibium at industry events.

Improving public documentation for clarity, grammar, or developer experience.

The Compensated Sphere: Bounties & Contracts

The compensated sphere covers high-reliability, high-accountability tasks critical to the stability and growth of the Vibium infrastructure.

Nature of Work:

Defined Scope: Tasks have specific technical requirements and fixed deadlines.

Accountability: Work is subject to rigorous review and performance standards.

Business Critical: Includes tasks that impact system uptime, security, or enterprise utility.

Compensation Structure:

Standard payments in USD or USDC.

Formalized service contracts or grant agreements.

1. Core Protocol Engineering

Conducting security audits and implementing critical vulnerability fixes.

Major architectural improvements requiring extensive deep-work (20+ hours).

Ownership and maintenance of official SDKs and core repositories.

2. High-Value Technical Assets

Enterprise-grade benchmarking and performance optimization testing.

Designing official documentation architecture and authoring deep technical guides.

Delivering roadmap features specifically tagged with official bounties.

3. Professional Representation

Paid speaking engagements at major industry conferences.

Leading official workshops and certification training.

Providing technical consulting and implementation for enterprise partners.

The Boundary Rules: Determining Compensation

A task must transition from the volunteer sphere to the compensated sphere if it meets any of the following criteria:

High Accountability: If failure to deliver would cause system outages, security risks, or significant reputational damage.

Scheduled Responsibility: If the role requires being "on duty," regular moderation shifts, or recurring obligations.

Operational Overhead: If the task involves internal maintenance, administrative coordination, or operations.

Proprietary Scope: If the output is intended for internal use only and is not released as open-source.

