Rule of Thumb: If a task becomes expected or relied upon for operations, it must be compensated.

The "Danger Zone" Test

Before assigning or accepting work, apply this test:

"If this task stops tomorrow, does a critical system or process break?"

No: The task is a volunteer contribution.

Yes: The task is a compensated responsibility.

The Ascension Path

Vibium prioritizes existing community members for paid opportunities. The standard progression path is as follows:

Contribute as an Ambassador or MVP to build a track record.

Demonstrate technical consistency and cultural alignment.

Ascend to invited bounties, fixed-term contracts, or core contributor roles.

Institutional Commitments

To maintain professional standards, Vibium adheres to the following:

No unpaid operational or administrative roles.

No "soft expectations" of free labor from community members.

No replacement of monetary compensation with merchandise or "exposure" for critical work.

No requirement for Ambassadors to serve as technical support staff.

Guiding Philosophy

Vibium is built by a community, but it is not sustained on unpaid labor. We believe that while creativity should be free and unburdened, professional responsibility must be fairly compensated.

We will never ask our community to do work that we would not pay for internally.
